  [2]
 In late 2022 and early 2023, that described crypto-y banks, and it  became=
 controversial that they were borrowing from the FHLBs.
It got the rest of the money by selling a bunch of its bond portfolio: At t=
he end of September it had $11.4 billion of bonds, $8.3 billion of them =E2=
=80=9Cavailable-for-sale=E2=80=9D (an accounting term meaning that Silverga=
te had to mark them on its books at their fair value) and others =E2=80=9Ch=
eld-to-maturity=E2=80=9D (meaning that Silvergate could mark them at cost a=
nd not worry about changes in market value). At the end of December, it had=
