=E2=80=9D

We have talked a lot over the last year about crypto shadow banks imploding=
. Often, when a crypto shadow bank implodes, its leader   will say that the=
re was a =E2=80=9Crun on the bank=E2=80=9D: It had valuable assets, but cus=
tomers asked for their money back all at once, so it had to dump the assets=
, so they lost value, so it didn=E2=80=99t have enough=C2=A0money to pay ba=
ck all the customers. I have been skeptical of these claims, because in gen=
eral the valuable assets were, like, magic beans that the crypto shadow ban=
k had invented itself. The crypto shadow bank=E2=80=99s assets =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0in the case of   Terra, of   FTX, of   Celsius, so many others =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0were mostly=C2=A0confidence in the shadow bank itself, and when that =
evaporated so did the assets.
Meanwhile in actual regulated US banking, the idea of a =E2=80=9Crun on the=
 bank=E2=80=9D is somewhat quaint.
  [6]
=C2=A0A run on the bank happens in, like,=C2=A0It=E2=80=99s a Wonderful Lif=
e, but in the real world of big US banks,  that particular dynamic =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0you hear some bad rumors about your bank, you rush to withdraw mon=
ey, the bank has to dump assets to get the money, it becomes insolvent =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0would be strange. In modern US banking, there is deposit insura=
nce to reassure small depositors. There are programs =E2=80=94=C2=A0the Fed=
eral Home Loan Banks, the Federal Reserve=E2=80=99s discount window =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0designed to make sure that a=C2=A0solvent=C2=A0bank can get cash t=
o pay out depositors. And there are capital and prudential regulations desi=
gned to make sure that the banks are solvent.
But Silvergate is having a real run on the bank! It has lost money, not by =
making dumb Bitcoin loans =E2=80=94=C2=A0the Bitcoin loans are fine =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0but by doing the normal business of banking, borrowing short (taki=
ng deposits from crypto firms) to lend long (buying Treasuries and munis). =
Silvergate=E2=80=99s assets are real boring normal stuff, and if=C2=A0its d=
epositors had kept their money at Silvergate, its bonds would have matured =
with plenty of money to pay them back. Instead, the depositors demanded the=
ir money back all at once, and Silvergate had to dump its long-term assets =
at big losses to repay them.
The story=C2=A0today=C2=A0is that Silvergate=E2=80=99s customers are withdr=
awing their money because they are worried=C2=A0about Silvergate, =E2=80=9C=
in light of recent developments & out of an abundance of caution,=E2=80=9D =
classic bank-run stuff. But that's not why they were withdrawing their mone=
y in late 2022, when the trouble started.=C2=A0Then, they were withdrawing =
their money because=C2=A0crypto had collapsed:=C2=A0Silvergate=E2=80=99s cr=
ypto-exchange customers faced withdrawals from=C2=A0their=C2=A0customers, s=
o they took their money out of Silvergate. The customers =E2=80=94=C2=A0cry=
pto exchanges =E2=80=94=C2=A0were the problem, not Silvergate.
It=E2=80=99s just last week that US regulators  warned banks about this:

The Board of Governors of the Federal Reserve System (Federal Reserve), the=
 Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation (FDIC), and the Office of the Comptr=
oller of the Currency (OCC) (collectively, the agencies) are issuing this s=
tatement on the liquidity risks presented by certain sources of funding fro=
m crypto-asset-related entities, and some effective practices to manage suc=
h risks. =E2=80=A6
Deposits placed by a crypto-asset-related entity that are for the benefit o=
f the crypto-asset-related entity=E2=80=99s customers (end customers). The =
stability of such deposits may be driven by the behavior of the end custome=
r or crypto-asset sector dynamics, and not solely by the crypto-asset-relat=
ed entity itself, which is the banking organization=E2=80=99s direct counte=
rparty. The stability of the deposits may be influenced by, for example, pe=
riods of stress, market volatility, and related vulnerabilities in the cryp=
to-asset sector, which may or may not be specific to the crypto-asset-relat=
ed entity. Such deposits can be susceptible to large and rapid inflows as w=
