th Wall Street and Main Street, there are plenty of each =E2=80=94 you=E2=
=80=99re now able to express that view via the magic of ETFs.
A pair of new products is launching Thursday that will help US investors be=
t either on or against the stock picks of the host of CNBC=E2=80=99s Mad Mo=
ney show, arguably the world=E2=80=99s most-famous financial pundit. =E2=80=
=A6
Matthew Tuttle, CEO of Tuttle Capital Management, has turned his attention =
to Cramer, fulfilling a long-running finance joke that the CNBC anchor shou=
ld get his own inverse fund.
=E2=80=9CIf he specifically says either buy, buy, buy a stock, then we=E2=
=80=99re gonna go short that stock at the next practical moment,=E2=80=9D T=
uttle told Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Trillions podcast, referring to the inverse =
strategy. =E2=80=9CIf he tells you he hates a stock or sell, sell, sell or =
something like that, then we=E2=80=99re gonna go long that name again at th=
e next kind of practical entry point.=E2=80=9D ...
The methodology behind the ETFs is decidedly low-tech. To design the portfo=
lios, which are equal weight, Tuttle and two colleagues watch Cramer=E2=80=
=99s television appearances throughout the day and monitor his Twitter acco=
unt. The result is two actively managed portfolios that hold between 20 to =
50 names with a high turnover rate, Tuttle said. Both products carry an exp=
ense ratio of 1.2%.=C2=A0

They=E2=80=99re called LJIM and SJIM, for long and short, respectively. Her=
e is  the website. Here is  the prospectus for SJIM:
Investment Objective: The Inverse Cramer Tracker ETF (the =E2=80=9CFund=E2=
=80=9D) seeks to provide investments results that are approximately the opp=
osite of, before fees and expenses, the results of the investments recommen=
ded by television personality Jim Cramer.=C2=A0
Oh yeah.
The Fund=E2=80=99s adviser monitors Cramer=E2=80=99s stock selection and ov=
erall market recommendations throughout the trading day as publicly announc=
ed on Twitter or his television programs broadcast on CNBC and sells Cramer=
=E2=80=99s stock recommendations short. The Fund goes short or long on stoc=
ks or ETFs, including Index ETFs and inverse Index ETFs, to take the opposi=
te side of Cramer=E2=80=99s announced market or sector view. The Fund=E2=80=
=99s portfolio is comprised generally of=C2=A020 to 50 equity securities of=
 any market capitalization of domestic and foreign issuers through American=
 Depositary Receipts, and/or ETFs if Cramer makes market or sector recommen=
dations. Should Cramer recommend buying any of the securities in the Fund=
=E2=80=99s portfolio, the Fund will dispose of those holdings. Should Crame=
r recommend selling any of the securities in the Fund=E2=80=99s portfolio, =
the Fund will keep those holdings. The adviser may also sell securities tha=
t have gone =E2=80=9Cstale=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94i.e., have been held for severa=
l weeks with no further commentary by Cramer. If Cramer does not take=C2=A0=
any view on any of the securities in the Fund=E2=80=99s portfolio, includin=
g when he is absent from CNBC or Twitter for any reason, the adviser furthe=
r retains discretion to sell positions if market conditions such as large s=
wings in either direction necessitate a sale because profit or loss targets=
 are met and replace them with securities that represent the opposite side =
of Cramer=E2=80=99s announced market or sector view. Under normal circumsta=
nces, the Fund will hold positions no longer than a 5-day trading week but =
could hold a position longer if Cramer continues to have a contrary opinion=
.=C2=A0
I feel like this is what the financial industry is all about? I love it. Th=
e prospectus is notably short on backtest data (there is none), presumably =
because it is hard to do a backtest on the strategy, presumably=C2=A0becaus=
e no one was sitting around making notes of all of Cramer=E2=80=99s recomme=
ndations for months=C2=A0before=C2=A0launching this thing. It is very funny=
 to have a job that is just sitting around watching Jim Cramer=E2=80=99s sh=
ow all day and doing the opposite of every trade he recommends, but you pro=
bably wouldn=E2=80=99t do it if you weren=E2=80=99t getting paid 1.2%.
I mean! You might do it if it had alpha? It=C2=A0is =E2=80=9Ca long-running=
 finance joke=E2=80=9D that doing the opposite of Cramer=E2=80=99s recommen=
dations could make you money. Presumably at some point some bored young per=
son dreaming of making it as a stock trader tried to actually do it? Watch =
TV, do the opposite of Cramer=E2=80=99s trades, get rich? Presumably that p=
erson did not get rich?=C2=A0Presumably if it worked people would just do i=
t, instead of selling it as an ETF; in general this is not a perfect heuris=
tic but it feels right here. Especially since both SJIM and LJIM exist, and=
 they can=E2=80=99t really=C2=A0both=C2=A0work. The point of these products=
 is not that Cramer=E2=80=99s recommendations have positive or negative alp=
ha; the point is that (1) the products are funny and (2) people might buy t=
hem for comedy and/or celebrity reasons?
Also, from the prospectus:
The Trust, the Fund and the adviser are not affiliated with Cramer or any o=
f the media by which his recommendations are communicated. Cramer is not in=
volved in the creation, management or operations of the Fund. The adviser d=
oes not in all cases perform fundamental investment analysis of securities =
bought, sold and held by the Fund. The primary factor for transacting in su=
ch securities or related securities is the fact that they are mentioned by =
Cramer.
Surely if one of these funds consistently outperforms the market, Cramer sh=
ould stop giving away free alpha to Tuttle and start running his own fund (=
or inverse fund) himself? It would be funny if it was the inverse one.=C2=
=A0

