<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A core feature of bank regulation is capital r=
equirements. If you are a bank, and you take $100 of deposits and make $100=
 of loans, and one of the loans defaults and you only get back $98, then yo=
u don=E2=80=99t have enough money to pay back all of your depositors, and t=
hat=E2=80=99s very bad. What regulators do is require that a bank that make=
s $100 of loans has to fund those loans with at most, say, $92 of deposits;=
 the other $8 has to come from the bank=E2=80=99s shareholders. Then if som=
e loans default and the bank only gets back $98, it can pay back all $92 of=
 deposits, and only the shareholders lose money.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Capital requirements are mostly =E2=80=9Crisk-=
based=E2=80=9D: You have to have about $8 of capital for every $100 of =E2=
=80=9Crisk-weighted assets,=E2=80=9D and different assets have different ri=
sk weights. A bank that makes a lot of sensible mortgage and business loans=
 might have to have $8 of capital for every $100 of loans, while a bank tha=
t, uh, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30710887.25=
